{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"HTML Tables","slug":"html-tables","subject":"HTML","category":"Web Development","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"20 minutes","prerequisites":["HTML Lists"],"learning_objectives":["Create tables with <table>, <tr>, <td>, and <th>","Understand row and column headers","Merge cells using rowspan and colspan","Group table content with <thead>, <tbody>, <tfoot>"],"theory":"# HTML Tables\n\nHTML tables allow web developers to arrange data into **rows and columns**.\n\n## Basic Tags\n*   `<table>`: The container for the table.\n*   `<tr>`: **Table Row**.\n*   `<th>`: **Table Header** (Bold and centered by default).\n*   `<td>`: **Table Data** (Standard cell).\n\n## Simple Table Example\n\n```html\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <th>Name</th>\n    <th>Age</th>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Alice</td>\n    <td>24</td>\n  </tr>\n</table>\n```\n\n## Merging Cells\n\n### Colspan (Merge Columns)\nTo make a cell span over multiple columns:\n```html\n<th colspan=\"2\">Full Name</th>\n```\n\n### Rowspan (Merge Rows)\nTo make a cell span over multiple rows:\n```html\n<td rowspan=\"2\">Data</td>\n```\n\n## Semantic Grouping\nFor long tables, you should group the content:\n*   `<thead>`: Header content.\n*   `<tbody>`: Body content.\n*   `<tfoot>`: Footer content (e.g., totals).\n\n```html\n<table>\n  <thead>...</thead>\n  <tbody>...</tbody>\n  <tfoot>...</tfoot>\n</table>\n```","syntax":"<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Data</td>\n  </tr>\n</table>","examples":[{"code":"<table border=\"1\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n       <th>Item</th>\n       <th>Price</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n       <td>Apple</td>\n       <td>$1</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>","output":"A table with headers 'Item', 'Price' and one row 'Apple', '$1'.","explanation":"border='1' is old school attributes. Modern tables are styled with CSS borders."},{"code":"<!-- Colspan Example -->\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <th colspan=\"2\">Contact Info</th>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Email</td>\n    <td>Phone</td>\n  </tr>\n</table>","output":"A header 'Contact Info' spanning two columns above Email and Phone.","explanation":"colspan merges cells horizontally."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using tables for layout","correction":"Never use tables to design the layout of a whole webpage. Use CSS Grid or Flexbox instead. Tables are ONLY for tabular data.","example":"❌ <table><tr><td>Sidebar</td><td>Content</td>... \n✅ display: flex;"},{"mistake":"Forgetting closing tags","correction":"Table structure breaks easily if you miss a </td> or </tr>.","example":"Always verify row counts match."}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"When should you use an HTML table?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"Use tables ONLY for tabular data (calendars, pricing lists, schedules). Do not use them for page layout."},{"question":"What is the difference between <th> and <td>?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"<th> is for header cells (usually bold/centered, semantic meaning of a label). <td> is for standard data cells."},{"question":"How do you merge two columns?","difficulty":"Intermediate","answer":"Use the colspan attribute on the <td> or <th> tag. E.g., <td colspan='2'>."}],"practice_problems":[{"difficulty":"Beginner","problem":"Create a 2x2 table with headers 'Country' and 'Capital', and one row of data.","hint":"Use tr for rows, th for headers, td for data.","solution":"<table>\n  <tr>\n    <th>Country</th><th>Capital</th>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>France</td><td>Paris</td>\n  </tr>\n</table>"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Financial Reports","description":"Stock market dashboards and bank statements use complex HTML tables to display numerical data grid-wise.","code":"<table><thead>...Results...</thead></table>"}],"exam_notes":["tr = Table Row","td = Table Data","th = Table Header","rowspan merges VERTICALLY","colspan merges HORIZONTALLY","Don't use tables for layout!"],"summary":"HTML Tables are the standard way to display structured data organized in rows and columns. While powerful for data representation, they should strictly be used for data and never for design layouts. Mastering cell merging with colspan and rowspan allows for complex data presentation.","order":34},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"html-document-structure","path":"content/html/html-document-structure.json","title":"HTML Document Structure","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"html-comments","path":"content/html/html-comments.json","title":"HTML Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"html-editors","path":"content/html/html-editors.json","title":"HTML Editors & Tools","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":4},{"slug":"html-elements","path":"content/html/html-elements.json","title":"HTML Elements","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":5},{"slug":"html-attributes","path":"content/html/html-attributes.json","title":"HTML Attributes","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":6},{"slug":"html-audio-video","path":"content/html/html-audio-video.json","title":"HTML Audio and Video","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":7},{"slug":"html-block-inline","path":"content/html/html-block-inline.json","title":"HTML Block and Inline Elements","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":8},{"slug":"html-canvas","path":"content/html/html-canvas.json","title":"HTML Canvas","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":9},{"slug":"html-data-attributes","path":"content/html/html-data-attributes.json","title":"HTML Data Attributes","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":10},{"slug":"html-debugging","path":"content/html/html-debugging.json","title":"HTML Debugging","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":11},{"slug":"html-drag-and-drop","path